# Architecture Plan

## Project Shape

This repository is a Vite + React + TypeScript static frontend. The current app
is a client-only clock UI with reusable hooks and colocated tests. The weather
batch should extend the existing shallow structure:

- `src/main.tsx`: React entry point and global stylesheet import.
- `src/App.tsx`: Top-level page composition for clock plus weather.
- `src/components/ClockDisplay.tsx`: Existing clock display.
- `src/components/FormatToggle.tsx`: Existing time-format switch.
- `src/components/CitySearch.tsx`: New manual city search/geocoding input.
- `src/components/WeatherCard.tsx`: New weather display and fallback surface.
- `src/hooks/useCurrentTime.ts`: Existing one-second clock state.
- `src/hooks/useFormatPref.ts`: Existing persisted time-format preference.
- `src/hooks/useGeolocation.ts`: Existing browser geolocation hook.
- `src/hooks/useWeather.ts`: New Open-Meteo current-weather fetch/caching hook.
- `src/types/weather.ts`: Shared weather, city, coordinates, and condition
  types if those shapes are needed by more than one hook/component.
- Colocated `*.test.ts(x)` files for hooks and components, with broader
  integration tests once the weather flow is assembled.
- `tests/e2e/`: Existing Playwright smoke coverage can be extended later if
  needed.

## Shared Types

Prefer narrow TypeScript types shared only where they cross module boundaries:

- `Coordinates`: `{ latitude: number; longitude: number }`.
- `WeatherCondition`: stable code/text/icon metadata derived from Open-Meteo
  weather codes.
- `WeatherData`: temperature, feels-like temperature, weather code, condition,
  coordinates, and fetched timestamp.
- `WeatherState`: data, loading flag, and structured error.
- `CitySearchResult`: city name, optional admin/country labels, latitude, and
  longitude.

Use Celsius by default because Open-Meteo returns metric units by default and no
issue asks for unit switching.

## Issue Dependencies

- #27 `useWeather` hook:
  - Depends only on existing React/Vite infrastructure.
  - Fetches `https://api.open-meteo.com/v1/forecast` with latitude/longitude,
    current temperature, apparent temperature, and weather code.
  - Caches the last successful result in `localStorage`.
- #28 city search with geocoding:
  - Independent of #27, but should reuse the same `Coordinates`/city types.
  - Calls Open-Meteo geocoding and persists the selected city in `localStorage`.
- #29 `WeatherCard` component:
  - Depends on #27, #28, and existing #25 `useGeolocation`.
  - Presents weather data, loading skeleton, errors, and manual-city fallback.
- #30 integrate weather card into `App.tsx`:
  - Depends on #29 and the assembled hook/component flow.
  - Places the card below the clock while keeping the centered layout.
- #31 unit and integration tests:
  - Depends on all weather hooks/components.
  - Should cover mocked weather fetches, geocoding, cache behavior,
    geolocation granted/denied paths, and weather card states.

## Key Design Decisions

- Keep the feature fully client-side: no backend, database, secrets, or API keys.
- Use Open-Meteo public endpoints directly from browser code.
- Store only small user-facing cache/preference values in `localStorage`: last
  weather response and selected city. Treat cache reads as best-effort and
  validate parsed data before use.
- Use structured errors instead of throwing from hooks so UI can fall back to
  city search when geolocation or API calls fail.
- Abort or ignore stale fetches on unmount and coordinate/city changes.
- Map Open-Meteo weather codes through a local helper/table so UI components do
  not know API-specific code meanings.
- Keep `WeatherCard` presentational where possible: receive weather state and
  fallback controls through props, while `App.tsx` owns the geolocation,
  selected-city, and weather-fetch wiring during integration.
- Keep styling consistent with the clock UI: Tailwind, restrained surfaces,
  light/dark variants, and stable dimensions for loading/error/data states.
